Domain create api now supports passing a view. You may pass the view id or name on the post call.
If you don't pass any of these, it is created with no view associated.
If you pass any of these, but the system can't find such a view, an

Fixing bugs regarding slave export The previous refactoring for more than one slave brought some
bugs because it tried to export zonefiles for slaves, before
creating them.

The original behavior of the system is to not export zonefiles
for slaves. This behavior was therefore preserved.

Another mistake was regarding disabling slaves on the conf file.
It is stated that just putting an empty ("") host for a slave
is enough for disabling it. This behavior wasn't persisted
on the cited refactoring and was now restored.

The last problem was on the revert method, that is supposed to
rollback the local git server and sync that version to the remote
servers. There was a problem when an error ocurred before the
commit/sync. That way the system tried to revert 'nothing'. Fixed.

Support for sibling domains added. Suppose you have the same domain on more than one view,
and that these views share some records.

On legacy code, if you got to edit the domain inside one view,
the domain on the other view would be unchanged, and you would
have an inconsistency. The fix was to always remember to do the
same change on all 'sibling' domains.

Now, when we import, we check if there's another domain already
saved with the same name. If that's the case, we 'merge' the records
of both.

This merging happen in two steps: firstly, we remove all
replicated records of the new domain. Secondly, we set the
former domain as the 'sibling' of this new one. This relation
persists forever, and can be seen on the edit page for this particular
domain.

When we export again, we rebuild the domains as if they were
independent, but now without inconsistency.

utime only changes the date of actually modified files. Now the utime call is done only for actually modified zonefiles.
If a domain wasn't updated since the last commit, it's utime isn't
modified.

Note1: For this feature to work, the button 'export' must be used.
  If one uses the 'export all' button, *all* zonefiles are considered
  modified, and utime is called in all of them, therefore.

Note2: it prevents a previous feature that was documented on this
  comment (that was removed as well):

  """
  (...) update 'mtime' of *all* non-slave domains, so that we may use
  the mtime as a criteria to identify the zonefiles that have been
  removed from BIND's config.
  """

Revert remote config when export fails. Now when the export fails, the local git repo is reset, and
this old config is exported again.

This is important, because previously when we had an error, the local
repo would be reset, but the bind server would be stuck with falsy
config.

It is important to note that we test with rndc-checkconf before
syncing with the server. Thus, if we have any problem locally, we
can just reset the git repo, since no info was sync to server.

The server info is sync to the last valid commit ONLY IF anything
was already sent on this export. This happens if we have an excetion
AFTER the sync_remote method call.

Exported zonefiles organized in subdirectories. The exported zonefiles are organized in subdirectories, based on
GloboDns::Config::SUBDIR_DEPTH.

Directories are created using up to GloboDns::Config::SUBDIR_DEPTH
characters from the domain names, to reduce the ammount of files
per directory, to ensure better performance.

Adding support to more than one slave the config/globodns.yml file now sets a master dns server and a list of slaves.

All the code related on importing/exporting and interface has been
changed to comply to more than one slave.

The export strategy may still be clumsy and it is still going to be
polished.

Exclude IPs in "match-clients" to force matching through "keys" The way Globo is attempting to use BIND views complicates the way we
must setup the servers to ensure that we're able to reach both views on
the master and slave servers. More especifically, BIND views are
supposed to use subnets that have no intersections -- i.e.
192.168.1.0/24 and 192.168.2.0/24. When the two subnets intersect, BIND
simply selects the first matching view. This is, supposedly, to simplify the
primary use case for views: defining a view for your intranet (i.e,
10.0.0.0/8), and another for everybody else (0.0.0.0/0).

Now, as stated initially, Globo is attempting to use views in a very
different way: to separate ipv4 from ipv6 addresses. The issue is that
the definition of the subnets in this case (0.0.0.0/0 and ::0/0) do not
create any actual subnets (both encompass the entire address spaces).
This means that the view selection will happen based on the type of the
IP address used to issue the query. *But*, if host originating the query
doesn't have an IP address of each type, it becomes impossible to query
for the view of the other type. An example might help clear things a
bit: on the QA environment, no server has an ipv6 address; so, there's
no way for the dnsapi server to issue queries on the domains/records
defined in the V6 view, nor for the slave server to transfers the
zones from the same view.

After a lot of reading and testing, I believe there are two solutions:
the first one -- which I skipped because I thought might be a bit too
limiting, is to require all servers to have an ipv6 address, set the
"transfer-source" statement accordingly in the definition of the slave
zones, and use the "-b" flag of the "dig" command to select the source
IP used to send the queries from the dnsapi server.

The second one, which is what this patch partially implements, is to use
the "key" statement to select the view. The "partially" is because the
patch actually augments the solution I've originally used to select the
views when implementing the "query" functionality long ago. At the time,
however, the tests didn't account for the fact the dnsapi server's IP
address could match the values from the "match-clients" statement of
both views. So, now, what we do is to explicitly remove the address of
the dnsapi and slave servers in the "match-clients" statement. And,
additionally, we explicitly set the "key" that should be used when
defining the "master" statement of a slave zone.

My preliminary tests in the QA environment seem to have worked well, but
this setup seems a bit fragile and it's absolutely possible I have
overlooked one or more use cases that will break under this setup.

Exclude "session.key" from the importer's rsync Since we're running the remote copies using the "dnsapi" user, we must now
exclude the "session.key" file. The reason is that it is created by the BIND
application itself, using the "named" user, and the permissions are set as 600
(so the "dnsapi" user can't access it and the rsync command will fail if we do
not explicitly exclude it).

Don't validate record names and recursive subdomains on import As per Marcus Bergo's request, do not validate the record names (i.e.,
no underscores) and recursive subdomains names (i.e., prevent creation
of the A record "test.dev.globo.com" as "test.dev" inside "globo.com" if
the subdomain "dev.globo.com" exists) when the domains is created by the
importer.

This should significantly decrease the number of changes required to
successfully import the original Globo.com BIND datasets.

token authentication path: the "X-Auth-Token" HTTP header.

Fix 'warnings' serialization The 'has_warnings?' method would run the validations, which caused the
warnings to be serialized on read-only operations (i.e., show, index).
So, the correct way to check if the 'warnings' should be serialialized
is by checking the 'warnings' method, which returns an
'ActiveModel::Error' instance.

Additionally, we must override the 'ActiveModel::become' method and
manually copy the '@warnings' instance variable.

Fix validation of record labels and content PTR and CNAME have a few special rules (as the labels aren't necessarily
hostnames). Also, the label validations were missing a few tweaks.

Revert and fix e4118640 When named.conf had no changes after an 'import', we'd check whether any
changes were available with 'git add --verbose' and only added a new
revision to the repository if 'git add' returned something. However,
this breaks future exports which depend on the timestamp of the last
revision, which should be the timestamp of the 'import' operation.

Therefore, we now skip the 'git add' check and force a new revision of
the 'named.conf' file by adding a comment at the end with the 'import'
timestamp.
Fix exclusion of view keys on importer

Fix recursive_domains validation on Domain to use full prefix We were searching for records using just the last "part" of the prefix
(i.e., if the domain was named "foo.bar.example.com", we'd search for
records named "foo" and "%.foo" on the domain "bar.example.com", then
"bar" and "%.bar" on the domain "example.com", and so on). But the rule
should use the "full" prefix (i.e., the second search in the previous
example should be "foo.bar" and "%.foo.bar" on "example.com").

Use 'keys' to select the view when issuing test DNS queries A problem we have is: how to select which view a test DNS query should

Replace 'domains#type' col with 'authority_type' and 'addressing_type' The previous method of differentiating reverse and normal domains using
the 'name' column does not scale (string comparisons are expensive,
and we woudn't be able to index the column the way we should). So I've
added a 'addressing_type' column and, in the mean time, replaced the
ambiguous 'type' column with 'authority_type'. So now we have two domain
classifications: by address type (REVERSE/NORMAL) and by authority
type (MASTER/SLAVE).

Additionally, I've set the 'ttl' column as nullable, since slave domains
do not need a TTL.

Speed up 'export' by tweaking the query that finds updated domains Previously we used a query to retrieve all domains and a query for each
domain, checking the 'updated_at' attribute of the associated records.
Now the 'per-domain' queries have been replaced with just one, we should
give us a measurable speed up ('export' now takes ~2 secs, down from ~4
secs).
Add a missing configuration key ('bind_group' under the 'test' env) The unit tests wouldn't run without it; should've added this long ago.

Fix handling of whitespace and newlines from the named.conf textarea We were adding extra new line characters at the end of the named.conf
content on each submit. And not handling CRLF properly.

Avoid problems due to sub-seconds timestamps differences on export Sometimes the filesytem would update a file's mtime with subseconds, but
the app-level comparison discarded the subsecond information and caused
and error when selecting the zonefiles to remove.

To avoid this problem, we now use a separate file to "touch" the files
when generating the zonefiles. Additionally, we explicitly set the
'change' timestamp in the unit test.
Don't update the 'updated_at' column when updating the serial on 'export'
Use different rndc port on unit tests Otherwise it conflicts with a running 'official' named server.
